Only one thing I would quibble with:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   ... build sea cities. Power them with SSPS energy.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I think that SSPS would be overkill. A sea city would be able to supply its power needs from any of a number of local sources. Wind, wave, Ocean Thermal Energy Conversion{OTEC}, PV, biomass digesters, solar thermal, etc.  Alone or in combination they should provide more then sufficient independent power. Each can also be used to produce hydrogen.<br>
OTEC has tremendous potential for sea cities:<br>
It simoultaneous supplies: (From the Department of Energy)<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Benefits of OTEC<br>
- Helps produce fuels such as hydrogen, ammonia, and methanol <br>
- Produces baseload electrical energy <br>
- Produces desalinated water for industrial, agricultural, and residential uses <br>
- Is a resource for on-shore and near-shore mariculture operations <br>
- Provides air-conditioning for buildings <br>
- Provides moderate-temperature refrigeration <br>
- Has significant potential to provide clean, cost-effective electricity for the future. <br>
<br>
OTEC's noneconomic benefits, which help us achieve global environmental goals, include these: <br>
<br>
- Promotes competitiveness and international trade <br>
- Enhances energy independence and energy security <br>
-Promotes international sociopolitical stability <br>
- Has potential to mitigate greenhouse gas emissions resulting from burning fossil fuels. <br>
- In small island nations, the benefits of OTEC include self-sufficiency, minimal environmental impacts, and improved sanitation and nutrition, which result from the greater availability of desalinated water and mariculture products.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->It also provide agricultural and maricultural nutrient in the rich cold deep seawater intake.<br>
