John.<br>
If the whole World becomes a farm there will be plenty of food but who would want to live in such a hellish place. The farmland used today would be better utilised as living space. The cost comparisons are really unimportant. Sure, it would be cheaper to farm Earth and not become a spacefaring nation. That's true. The argument only becomes valid however if that is our intention. To never leave Earth.<br>
Now if we are planning on conquering space anyway, and colonising every place that can be made habitable, humanity will take centuries to fill up those places. Simply because there is an almost endless amount of space out there. Maybe thousands of years before any sign of congestion appears. Maybe never. Even if 10 children families become the norm. That doesn't mean farming will be kept down to the levels required to feed current population levels. To be on the safe side everyone will ofcourse try and grow extra. What do you do with it if you can't eat it? You sell it. The amount of space available for off Earth agriculture is staggering. The product will be so plentiful that prices will drop well below Earth crops. They would likely sell cheaper to begin with. Just to get rid of it. The only other option is recycling it and that really wouldn't be necessary. Resources will be plentiful.<br>
As I said earlier, sending shipments is a simple matter of shoving a crate toward Earth. The time in transit for the frozen cargo to arrive is unimportant as long as it gets there. On being caught by a space habitat near Earth it is unloaded. The crate can be kicked back again for another shipment. Space radiation is the only problem I can see. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A> at: 8/30/02 4:30:00 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 661<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/30/02 8:44 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=92.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Sea Farming: not too far out</span><hr size=1> Your whole comments to John is a simple re-statement of your original comments. You are not considering the comparative scales required to accomplish your proposal. That is the reason for my asking for at least order-of-maginitude scale estimates. I think that you will find that your proposal is way out of balance compared to terrestrial alternatives.<br>
